# Line endings policy
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Dockmesh is cross-platform for development (Windows/macOS/Linux) but every
# production artefact runs on Linux. Store everything as LF in the repo so
# diffs are clean regardless of who's contributing.
#
# `text=auto` tells Git to detect text files automatically.
# `eol=lf` tells Git to write LF line endings on checkout on every OS, not
# CRLF on Windows. Combined, they stop the "LF will be replaced by CRLF the
# next time Git touches it" warning storm for Windows contributors.

* text=auto eol=lf

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Binary files — never touch these, regardless of auto-detection
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.ico binary
*.webp binary
*.pdf binary
*.zip binary
*.tar binary
*.tar.gz binary
*.tgz binary
*.woff binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf binary
*.eot binary
*.db binary
*.sqlite binary

# Go compiled artefacts (normally .gitignored, but be explicit)
*.exe binary

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Force LF explicitly on files where tooling cares about it
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Shell scripts must be LF to work on Linux
*.sh text eol=lf

# systemd units
*.service text eol=lf

# Go source — Go's gofmt enforces LF anyway, but this makes intent explicit
*.go text eol=lf

# Makefiles require LF
Makefile text eol=lf
